   * *OASIS Support*
      * Have already released CVMFS client and OASIS packages
      * Software team is working on some small updates (mainly OSG configuration)
      * Release team is leading the group effort to complete and integrate documentation

   * *SHA-2 Testing*
      * Release team is completely one last round of testing, this time with !DigiCert SHA-2 certificates
      * Hope to finish testing very soon
      * Will provide documentation on recommended minimum OSG Software versions (by component)

   * *Ongoing Updates and Support*
      * Software: Tarball client bug fixes, Globus/SGE SEG, SLURM (still in testing), lots more
      * Tickets (GOC and JIRA)

---+++ Top Concerns

   * *Defining Technology, Software, and Release Teams*
      * Responsibilities: We need to finish proposal, share, get approval (OSG Planning Retreat, next week)
      * Staffing
         * We have a good core defined for each team
         * Exact staffing percentages will be flexible and determined by !BrianB as needed
         * Still working on hiring in some places
         * Still defining some roles and contributions

   * *Multiple Important Projects*
      * See above for current list
      * Also getting increasing pressure from HTCondor team to take on more packaging tasks
      * Mitigation strategies:
         * Technology, Software, Release, Production, and as needed Security teams coordinate closely and often
         * We are prioritizing tasks carefully, while also keeping an eye on the longer term and upcoming needs
         * !TimT will raise warning flags as appropriate
      * Outlook: Still cautiously optimistic!

   * *Tracking Upstream Changes*
      * Example: Still had condor-7.8.6 long after 7.8.8 had been released
      * We package so many upstream components, that it is very difficult to track changes to all of them
      * Nominally assigned to the Release team now, but it is a big task
      * Need to work with !BrianB and !TimT to come up with a real plan here

   * *Slowed or Delayed Projects*
      * Documentation: Affects end-user experience &amp;mdash; chipping away at most important tasks
      * Testing: Little progress lately; hoping Release team can better define manual test cases
      * Configuration management: Affects end-user experience &amp;mdash; not started
      * Debian support: Affects who can use OSG Software &amp;mdash; not started
      * Community packaging, especially w.r.t. EPEL: Affects effort &amp;mdash; not really started, but Java is improving

